List All Possible Audience Segments

get
https://api.mediamath.com/api/v2.0
/audience_segments

The audience_segments API is used to target strategies based on third-party segments.

Targeting audience segments is a two-step process:

  1. Find available audience segments in T1
  2. Assign audience segments to a strategy

Find Available Audience Segments

The audience segments are organized as a taxonomy (tree) in T1. In order to retrieve audience segments, start with the top-level nodes, then recursively fetch child nodes for each level thus retrieved.

The first level in the audience segments taxonomy contains a root node for each data provider available in T1.

The root node can be found by calling the Audience Segments DMP API to get a list of the venders an advertiser has access to.

  • GET /dmp/v2.0/audience_segments/vendors/focus/advertiser={advertiser_id}

Once the audience segment id for an entity at the root node is known, it is possible to get information on the child audience segments of that entity

  • GET /api/v2.0/audience_segments?full=*&parent={parent_id}&advertiser_id={advertiser_id}

Second-level nodes themselves have child audience segments, so the process can be repeated as needed.

Formerly, Audence Segments could also be used to apply contextual targeting provided by Integral Ad Science; however, this was deprecated. Please see targeting_segments for instructions to apply contextual targeting.

Special Behavior of ?q=

Queries like GET /audience_segments?q=(123) automatically have extra filters applied to them:

  • parent_audience_segment_id IS NULL - only top-level nodes are returned.
  • type = 'normal' - custom (private) segments are not returned.

You can still use ?q= to retrieve child and private nodes. To do so you have to explicitly add one or more of the following query parameters that you have permission to access:

  • GET /audience_segments?q=(123)&organization_id=567
  • GET /audience_segments?q=(123)&agency_id=890
  • GET /audience_segments?q=(123)&advertiser_id=976

Query parameters: full=* will provide fields beyond entity_type, id, name (which is why those 3 list as required in the response) sort_by can use any response field with can use audience_vendor but not taxonomy
